SIMPLE: fixation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fixation
<hw>Fix*a"tion</hw> <pr>(f⟦icr⟧ks*⟦amac⟧"sh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[Cf. F. <ets>fixation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
fixing, or the state of being fixed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An unalterable <qex>fixation</qex> of resolution.</q>
<rj><qau>Killingbeck.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To light, created in the first day, God gave no proper place or
<qex>fixation</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Marked stiffness or absolute <qex>fixation</qex> of a joint.</q>
<rj><qau>Quain.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>fixation</qex> and confinement of thought to a few
objects.</q> <rj><qau>Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of uniting chemically with a solid substance
or in a solid form; reduction to a non-volatile condition; -- said of
gaseous elements.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The act or process of ceasing to be fluid and
becoming firm.</def> <rj><au>Glanvill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A state of resistance to evaporation or
volatilization by heat; -- said of metals.</def>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fixative</ent>⟦br⟧
